[2026-07-20T12:22:50.208Z] [INFO]   "description": "gh pr edit 811 --title \"fix(ci): unblock releases from historical evidence records; harden macOS sign diagnostics\" --body \"$(cat <<'EOF'\nFixes #810\n\nFull evidence and analysis: [`dev/log/issues/810/pulls/811/analysis.md`](https://github.com/link-assistant/formal-ai/blob/issue-810-9b3071713a8e/dev/log/issues/810/pulls/811/analysis.md)\n\n## What was failing\n\nBoth default-branch runs named in the issue are at `bd0bac88`. Every job passed except:\n\n| Run | Job |\n| --- | --- |\n| [29737218421](https://github.com/link-assistant/formal-ai/actions/runs/29737218421) CI/CD Pipeline | Auto Release |\n| [29738571290](https://github.com/link-assistant/formal-ai/actions/runs/29738571290) Desktop Release | Build macos-arm64 / macos-x64 (+ SHA256SUMS cascade) |\n\nTwo independent defects.\n\n## Defect A — the evidence gate deadlocked every release (fixed)\n\n```\nError recording self-hosting release metric: no committed Formal-AI-Evidence\nin 10e65ae2 records session issue-804-claude-20260720\n```\n\n`scripts/self-hosting-metric.rs` requires an evidence document to contain its own session id. Commit `10e65ae2`'s does not (`git show 10e65ae2:…/analysis.md | grep -c issue-804-claude-20260720` → `0`).\n\nThe timeline is what makes this fatal: the `evidence-check` gate was added in `39fdef91`, **after** `10e65ae2` merged. `record_release` measures `<last tag>..HEAD`, so that commit sits in the release range until a new tag is cut — and cutting a tag requires the release to succeed. Closed loop; no future commit could fix it.\n\n**Fix:** an explicit `EvidencePolicy`. The pull-request gate stays `Strict` and still hard-fails new malformed records before they reach `main`. `record_release` is `Lenient`: it warns and leaves the commit unattributed, so the metric can only ever under-report, never over-report.\n\n**Test:** `a_malformed_historical_evidence_record_cannot_deadlock_a_release` reproduces the exact shape of `10e65ae2` and asserts both halves — `measure()` still errors, `record_release()` succeeds with `self_authored_commits == 0`. `5 passed; 0 failed`.\n\n## Defect B — bundled Chrome framework seal (instrumented, not yet fixed)\n\n```\n…/Contents/Resources/browser-runtime/Frameworks/Google Chrome for Testing Framework.framework:\n  unsealed contents present in the root directory of an embedded framework\n```\n\nThe logs prove the custom sign hook **was** invoked (electron-builder's own `• executing custom sign` marker, plus `--timestamp=none` from our `optionsForFile`), but contain **zero** `[adhoc-sign-mac]` lines despite `FORMAL_AI_MACOS_SIGN_DEBUG=1`. So it is still unknown whether the ignore predicate was consulted and said \"sign it\" or was never called — the two need different fixes, and guessing between them is how the previous two attempts went.\n\nPer the issue's instruction to add diagnostics when the data is insufficient:\n\n- `log()` now writes via `fs.writeSync(2, …)`. Async `process.stderr.write()` on a pipe loses whatever is queued when electron-builder aborts; a synchronous fd-2 write cannot. If the banner is still missing next run, the executing module is not this one.\n- The ignore predicate carries `stats`, reported as `ignore predicate: considered=N skipped=M` from a `finally` block, so it is emitted **on failure too**. `considered=0` vs `skipped=0` are very different diagnoses.\n- The per-file trace stays behind `FORMAL_AI_MACOS_SIGN_DEBUG`, **off by default**. Only two summary lines are unconditional.\n\nThe analysis document also argues that the durable fix is structural — ship the browser runtime as an archive expanded on first launch, so `codesign` never walks into a bundle it did not lay out — rather than further ignore-rule tuning.\n\n## Deliberately not done\n\n- **Upstream reports.** The `@electron/osx-sign` array-`ignore` behaviour is real and already worked around in-repo, but filing before the counters land would be filing a guess.\n- **Template comparison** against the three `link-foundation/*-ai-driven-development-pipeline-template` repos. Neither observed failure originates in template-derived workflow structure, so this is separate work; it is recorded as an open gap in §5 of the analysis rather than silently dropped.\nEOF\n)\" && gh pr ready 811 && echo OK",
